With UDS a new structure for displaying Measured values on tester is established. The old structure of the
MVB is no longer present.
With UDS every value which is wanted to be displayed on tester has to be de?ned in an ODX container and a
speci?c Identi?er has to assigned to this variable. Special conversions can be de?ned in the ODX container.
For every aggregate identi?er of the developer measured values range are reserved. The range of the de-
veloper is de?ned 0x1000 - 0x16FF. The ID?s are reserved depending on the number of values already, the
smaller 30, normal 40, and extended 50 ID?s reserved.

DGNC, UDS - SID 10h: diagnosticSessionControl Service
13.6 UDS - SID 10h: diagnosticSessionControl Service
� FUNCTION DESCRIPTION:
� General information:
The DiagnosticSessionControl service is used to enable different diagnostic sessions in the server(s). A diag-
nostic session enables a speci?c set of diagnostic services and/or functionality in the server(s). It also enables
a data link layer dependent set of timing parameters applicable for the started session.
� Description:
In this service, the server(s) reports data link layer speci?c parameter values valid for the enabled diagnostic
session (e.g. timing parameter values).
There shall always be exactly one diagnostic session active in a server. A server shall always start the default
diagnostic session when powered up. If no other diagnostic session is started, then the default diagnostic
session shall be running as long as the server is powered.
Whenever the client requests a new diagnostic session, the server shall send the DiagnosticSessionControl
positive response message before the timings of the new session become active in the server. If the server is
not able to start the requested new diagnostic session, then it shall respond with a DiagnosticSessionControl
negative response message and the current session shall continue.
� Application conditions
Initialisation: after reset, after IGK on
Recurrence: the service scheduler calls this service on demand (client request)
Activation: mentioned in the Application Incidence of the service.
Deactivation: mentioned in the Application Incidence of the service.

13.10 UDS - SID 19h: readDTCInformation Service
13.10.1 Purpose
This service allows a client to read server resident Diagnostic Trouble Code (DTC) information. This service
allows the client to retrieve DTC informations as following:
? Retrieve the list of DTC?smatching a client de?ned DTC status mask (02h).
The ReportDTCByStatusMask parameter speci?es that the server shall transmit to the client a list of DTCs
present in dynamic failure memory and corresponding status matching a client de?ned status mask.
? Retrieve DTCExtendedData for a client de?ned DTC mask (06h).
The ReportDTCExtendedDataRecordByDTCNumberparameter shall transmit to the client the DTCExtended-
DataRecord(s) (driving cycle counter) associated with a client de?ned DTC number and DTCExtended-
Data record number (FFh for all records).
The server shall report one DTCExtendedData records in a single response message, except the case
when the DTCExtendedDataRecordNumber is equal to FFh or 8Fh.

INOUT<PRM_FRF_LAST_USED_IDX>, index of last written ENVD
INOUT<PRM_FRF_LENGTH>, length of written data
INOUT<PRM_FRF_REFERENCE>, outputstream

13.12 UDS - SID 22h: readDataByIdenti?er Service
� FUNCTION DESCRIPTION:
� General information:
The ReadDataByIdenti?er service allows the client to request data record values from the server identi?ed
by one or more dataIdenti?ers. The client request message contains one or more two (2) byte dataIdenti?er
values that identify data record(s) maintained by the server. The format and de?nition of the dataRecord shall
be vehicle manufacturer or system supplier speci?c.
� Description:
The server shall limit the number of dataIdenti?ers that can be simultaneously requested as agreed upon by
the vehicle manufacturer and system supplier.
Upon receiving a ReadDataByIdenti?er request, the server shall access the data elements of the records spec-
i?ed by the dataIdenti?er parameter(s) and transmit their value in one single ReadDataByIdenti?er positive
response containing the associated dataRecord parameter(s). The request message may contain the same
dataIdenti?er multiple times. The server shall treat each dataIdenti?er as a separate parameter and respond
with data for each dataIdenti?er as often as requested.
� Application conditions
Initialisation: after reset, after IGK on
Recurrence: client (tester) request
Activation:
Deactivation:

13.13.3.71 Subsystem Identi?cation data - from 22,60,00 to 22,6F,FF
13.13.3.72 only If NLC_DIAG_CLAS_4_ENA = 1
This DID s are identi?cation data of subbus control units(SBCU), so the requests and responses have to trans-
fered between SBCU and diagnostic tester tool by the engine control unit(subbus master) . The engine control
unit receive the request from the diagnostic tester tool and transmits the related request to the SBCU via
the Diag Client(DGCL). The request and response handling between the engine control unit and the SBCU is
managed and evaluated by the Diag Client.
� DGCL interface description:
Icsp_DgCl_Start:
DGNC has to transmitt a request via API Icsp_DgCl_Start to DGCL.
- The API returns OK in case the Diag client could execute the request immediately.
- The API returns NOK in case the request isn t supported.
- The API returns BUSY in case there is already a request active.
Remark: OK will be returned only at start of a new request(?rst call). When a request is still started by
DGCL, the API returns BUSY.
Icsp_DgCl_GetData:
DGNC has to call the API Icsp_DgCl_GetData to get the reponse from the SBCU via the DGCL. When the return
value of Icsp_DgCl_Start is OK or BUSY the API Icsp_DgCl_GetData has to be called to poll the status of the
active request.
- The API returns OK in case the data are copied to the given DGNC buffer.
- The API returns NOK in case the request could not executed(e.g. wrong handling, buffer size is to
small)
- The API returns BUSY in case the request is still in progress.
General demands:
? During the execution of a request by the diagnostic client the 78 response handling has to be managed
by DGNC.
? To support multiple DID requests a buffer handling is implemented to save the responses from DGCL un-
til all responses are available. The subsystem DID s will be managed one after another, so the transmitted
responses have to be stored in a temporary buffer.

13.13.3.87 InUseMonitoringPerformanceRatio(Rate Based Monitoring) overview
� General information:
The RBM data are transmitted from the ECU to the diagnostic tester by a ?xed sequence (see state diagram
below).This sequence is started by service IUMPR_ID1(0x00FF), witch transmits general RBM informations and
initialzes the record number to the ?rst RBM diagnosis. Then service IUMPR_ID2(0x00FE: odd RBM record
number) has to be send to get the RBM data of the ?rst diagnosis. After that the order of service IUMPR_ID2
and service IUMPR_ID3(0x00FD: even RBM record number) could be choosen arbitrarily until the last record
number is reached. If a ID(IUMPR_ID2 or IUMPR_ID3) is called multiple then the RBM data of the same diagnosis
will be updated each time. At transition from service IUMPR_ID2 to IUMPR_ID3 or at transition from IUMPR_ID3
to IUMPR_ID2 the next diagnosis will be selected and the corresponding RBM data will be transmited.
CTR_DIAG_RBM_UDS is the number of the selected RBM diagnosis, it is intialised to 1 at start of IUMPR(IUMPR_
ID1 received). The counter will be incremented if the next diagnosis is selected(at transition from service
IUMPR_ID2 to IUMPR_ID3 or at transition from IUMPR_ID3 to IUMPR_ID2).
RBM_REC_NR is the failure memory internal record number of the RBM diagnosis, it isn?t identical with the
transmitted record number of the selected diagnosis CTR_DIAG_RBM_UDS. RBM_REC_NR is updated by ERRM
interfaces ACTION_ERRM_Reset_rbm_rec_nr and ACTION_ERRM_Increment_rbm_rec_nr.
NR_DIAG_RBM_UDS is the number of used RBM diagnoses. If a ERRM version with calibratable RBM(e.g. ERRM
4.13.0) is used then it is possible to disable RBM diagnostic instances by calibration, so the number of used RBM
diagnoses isn?t ?x(<=NC_NR_DIAG_RBM). Without RBM calibration functionality NR_DIAG_RBM_UDS is set to
NC_NR_DIAG_RBM.

13.13.3.91 OBD Mode overview
� General information:
With service 22 ID?s F4xx, F6xx, F8xx data of the OBD system could be read.
supported ID's  OBD mode  
F4xx  mode 1 
F6xx  mode 6 
F8xx  mode 9 
 
Depending on the diagnostic tester request, the service 22 functionality calls the OBDC service interpreter
by ACTION_OBDC_ReqOBDServices. If the requested ID is available the service interpreter transmits the OBD
data. The format of this data is identical to the data of corresponding OBD mode.
It is required to support only the calibrated OBD PID?s(0xF4xx), MID?s(0xF6xx) and TID?s(0xF8xx) via service
22. So bypassing of the OBD calibration isn t allowed.

� FUNCTION DESCRIPTION:
� General information:
The ReadMemoryByAddress service allows the client to request memory data from the server via provided
starting address and size of memory to be read.
Special solution for EEPROM emulation (DFLASH):
With EEPROM emulation virtual addresses are used for reading non volatile data.
virtual address:
1.byte: 0xE0 (code for EEPROM (emulation))
2.byte: channel number
3.-4.byte: offset for start address of requested data
� Application conditions
Initialisation: after reset, after IGK on
Recurrence: client (tester) request

� FUNCTION DESCRIPTION:
� General information:
The purpose of this service is to provide a means to access data and/or diagnostic services, which have re-
stricted access for security, emissions, or safety reasons. Diagnostic services for downloading/uploading rou-
tines or data into a server and reading speci?c memory locations from a server are situations where security
access may be required.
� Description:
The security concept uses a seed and key relationship as below:
- client requests the ?Seed?
- server sends the ?Seed?
- client sends the ?Key? (appropriate for the Seed received)
- server responds that the ?Key? was valid and that it will unlock itself
The message ?ow during security access.

Figure 13.16.1: Table: SecurityAccess Message Flow
A speci?c time delay shall be required before the server can positively respond to a service Security Access
requestSeed message from the client
- after server power up/reset and
- after a certain number of false access attempts.
If this delay timer is supported then the delay shall be activated after the third false access attempt has been
reached or when the server is powered up/reset and a previously performed SecurityAccess service has failed
due to a single false access attempt. After ?nishing blocking time, three additional attempts are possible. If
you send 3 wrong keys to the ECU again, the blocking time is doubled. This procedure is done till 255 minutes
blocking time is reached.

13.19.2 Different communication types (communicationType)
This parameter is bit coded value, which shall allow controlling multiple communication types at the same

13.20.1 Purpose
The WriteDataByIdenti?er service allows the client to write information into the server at an internal location
speci?ed by the provided data identi?er.
The RecordDataIdenti?er parameter identi?es data records maintained by the server. This data is transmitted

RequestSequenceError This response code indicates that the requested action will

SecurityAccessDenied This response code indicates that the requested action will not 
be taken because the server's security strategy has not been 
satisfied by the client. 
The server shall send this response code if one of the following 
cases occur: 
the test conditions of the server are not met, 
the required message sequence e.g. 
DiagnosticSessionControl, securityAccess is not met, 
the client has sent a request message which requires an 
unlocked server. 
RequestOutOfRange the requested RecordDataIdentifier is not supported. 
Any data transmitted in the request message is invalid.

13.22 UDS - SID 2Fh: inputOutputControlByIdenti?er Service
13.22.1 Purpose
This service is used to substitute a value for an input signal, internal ECU function and/or control an output of
an electronic system.
The InputOutputControlByIdenti?er message references the input and/or output signal via the InputOut-
putIdenti?er (see InputOutputControlByIdenti?er Service [2Fh] Application Incidence speci?cation for the ap-
plicable range).
The InputOutputControlParameter(IOCP) byte describes how the server has to control its inputs and/or
outputs.
hex  Names  Mnemonic  
00 ReturnControlToECU : 
This value shall indicate to the server that the client does no longer have control 
about the input or/and output signal(s) referenced by the InputOutputIdentifier.  
RCTECU 
03 ShortTermAdjustment:  
This value shall indicate to the server that it is requested to adjust the current 
state of the input or/and output signal(s) referenced by the InputOutputIdentifier in 
RAM to the value(s) included in the ControlOptionRecord parameter(s). 
STA 
 
The ControlState parameter 2 shall include information required by the server s input and/or output.
Hex: 
 
Description-ControlState#2: 
 
Cvt. 
 
00-FA  Timer 
These values force a time (timer) for parallel controlling of certain signal 
conditions. The resolution is done in seconds/Bit (1/s), i.e. the requested 
conditions can be holded maximal 250s. 
 
M  
FB-FE  Reserved 
 
- 
FF  InfiniteTiming - NoTimingDefined 
This value represent a endless/no time period (permanent control)

� FUNCTION DESCRIPTION:
� General information:
The transferData service is used by the client to transfer data either from the client to the server (download)
or from the server to the client (upload).
The data transfer direction is de?ned by the preceding RequestDownload or RequestUpload service. If the
client initiated a RequestDownload the data to be downloaded is included in the parameter(s) transferRe-
questParameter in the TransferData request message(s). If the client initiated a RequestUpload the data to
be uploaded is included in the parameter(s) transferResponseParameter in the TransferData response mes-
sage(s).
� Description:
The transferData service request includes a blockSequenceCounter to allow for an improved error handling in
case a TransferData service fails during a sequence of multiple TransferData requests.
� Application conditions

Recurrence: client (tester) request

? If a TransferData request for download data is correctly received and processed in the server but the
positive response message does not reach the client then the client would determine an application
layer timeout and would repeat the same request (including the same blockSequenceCounter). The
server would receive the repeated TransferData request and could determine based on the included
blockSequenceCounter that this TransferData request is repeated. The server would send the positive
response message immediately without writing the data once again into its memory.
? If the TransferData request for download data is not received correctly in the server then the server
would not send a positive response message. The client would determine an application layer timeout
and would repeat the same request (including the same blockSequenceCounter). The server would
receive the repeated TransferData request and could determine based on the included blockSequence-
Counter that this is a new TransferData. The server would process the service and would send the
positive response message.

This service shall used to indicate to a server (or servers) that a client is still connected to the vehicle and that
certain diagnostic services and/or communication that have been previously activated are to remain active.
This service shall used to keep one or multiple servers in a diagnostic session other than the defaultSession.

13.29.4 HeartBeat TesterPresent
This service shall support HeartBeat TesterPresent request with following conditions:
The request should be on different CAN ID i.e., functional CAN ID for diagnostic services.
The request should be always with suppressPosRspMsgIndicationBit (bit 7) set to 1.
Note: The heartbeat TesterPresent should reset the S3 CAN _SERV ER_MAX timeout counter and keep the
non-default session alive.

tions are true, then only the corresponding service shall be called.

go on Influence of ECF Off Pattern

This image is a **state diagram**, which can be precisely modeled using Stateflow, an integral part of Simulink for designing complex supervisory logic and state machines. Therefore, it is appropriate to analyze it in the context of automotive systems engineering and Simulink.

## Function

This state diagram describes the logical flow for handling diagnostic requests related to **In-Use Monitoring Performance Ratio (IUMPR)**, specifically within a **Rate-Based Monitoring (RBM)** context. Its primary function is to manage the sequence of receiving and responding to requests for different IUMPR data identifiers (ID1, ID2, ID3), ensuring correct diagnostic flow, handling out-of-sequence requests, and deactivating monitoring when the diagnostic process concludes or encounters specific errors. It dictates when specific IUMPR data can be read and how the system should react to various requests.

## Inputs

The key inputs that trigger state transitions and actions are:

*   **`IUMPR_ID1 received`**: An event signaling a request for IUMPR data identifier 1.
*   **`IUMPR_ID2 received`**: An event signaling a request for IUMPR data identifier 2.
*   **`IUMPR_ID3 received`**: An event signaling a request for IUMPR data identifier 3.
*   **`select first diagnosis`**: An internal action or condition to initialize the diagnostic process to the first available diagnosis.
*   **`select next diagnosis`**: An internal action or condition to advance the diagnostic process to the next available diagnosis.
*   **`last diagnosis reached`**: A boolean condition indicating that all available diagnostic data for a specific IUMPR ID has been processed.

## Outputs

The key outputs generated by the system are diagnostic responses and state changes:

*   **`PR` (Positive Response)**: Indicates that the received request was processed successfully.
*   **`NR:CNC` (Negative Response: Conditions Not Correct)**: Indicates that the request could not be fulfilled because certain conditions were not met (e.g., trying to read beyond the last available diagnosis).
*   **`NR:RSE` (Negative Response: Request Sequence Error)**: Indicates that the received request was out of the expected sequence for the current state.
*   **State Changes**: The system transitions between defined states: `DEAC`, `START (IUMPR-ID1)`, `ODD (IUMPR-ID2)`, `EVEN (IUMPR-ID3)`.

## Logic Flow

The system operates through distinct states, primarily differentiating between an inactive and an active monitoring phase.

1.  **`DEAC (RBM deactive)` State (Initial State)**:
    *   The system begins in this state, where Rate-Based Monitoring is inactive.
    *   **Activation:** Upon receiving `IUMPR_ID1`, the system performs the action `select first diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and transitions into the `RBM active` superstate, landing specifically in the `START (IUMPR-ID1)` sub-state.
    *   **Error Handling:** If `IUMPR_ID2` or `IUMPR_ID3` is received while in `DEAC` (which are out of sequence for activation), the system issues an `NR:RSE` and remains in the `DEAC` state.

2.  **`RBM active` Superstate**: This superstate groups all active monitoring states:

    *   **`START (IUMPR-ID1)` State**:
        *   This is the entry point for active RBM.
        *   **Self-Loop/Refresh:** If `IUMPR_ID1` is received, the system performs `select first diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and remains in `START`. This allows for re-reading the initial diagnostic data.
        *   **Sequence Progression:** If `IUMPR_ID2` is received, the system issues a `PR` and transitions to the `ODD (IUMPR-ID2)` state, progressing the diagnostic sequence.
        *   **Sequence Error:** If `IUMPR_ID3` is received, the system issues an `NR:RSE` and remains in `START`, as ID3 is not expected at this point.

    *   **`ODD (IUMPR-ID2)` State**:
        *   Reached from `START` by receiving `IUMPR_ID2`.
        *   **Reset/Restart Sequence:** If `IUMPR_ID1` is received, the system performs `select first diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and transitions back to `START (IUMPR-ID1)`. This allows resetting the diagnostic flow from the beginning.

*   **`ODD (IUMPR-ID2)` State**:
        *   Reached from `START` by receiving `IUMPR_ID2`.
        *   **Reset/Restart Sequence:** If `IUMPR_ID1` is received, the system performs `select first diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and transitions back to `START (IUMPR-ID1)`. This allows resetting the diagnostic flow from the beginning.
        *   **Iterate `ID2`:** If `IUMPR_ID2` is received, the system performs `select next diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and remains in `ODD`. This suggests iterating through multiple `IUMPR_ID2` diagnoses.
        *   **Sequence Progression:** If `IUMPR_ID3` is received, the system issues a `PR` and transitions to the `EVEN (IUMPR-ID3)` state.
        *   **Deactivation due to Conditions Not Correct:** If `IUMPR_ID3` is received *AND* the `last diagnosis reached` condition is true, the system issues an `NR:CNC` and transitions back to the `DEAC` state. This signifies an attempt to request further data (ID3) when no more diagnoses are available.

    *   **`EVEN (IUMPR-ID3)` State**:
        *   Reached from `ODD` by receiving `IUMPR_ID3`.
        *   **Reset/Restart Sequence:** If `IUMPR_ID1` is received, the system performs `select first diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and transitions back to `START (IUMPR-ID1)`.
        *   **Sequence Progression/Return:** If `IUMPR_ID2` is received, the system issues a `PR` and transitions back to the `ODD (IUMPR-ID2)` state. This indicates a cyclical progression between ID2 and ID3 after ID1.
        *   **Iterate `ID3`:** If `IUMPR_ID3` is received, the system performs `select next diagnosis`, issues a `PR`, and remains in `EVEN`. Similar to ID2, this allows iterating through multiple `IUMPR_ID3` diagnoses.
        *   **Deactivation due to Conditions Not Correct:** If `IUMPR_ID2` is received *AND* the `last diagnosis reached` condition is true, the system issues an `NR:CNC` and transitions back to the `DEAC` state. This signifies an attempt to request further data (ID2) when no more diagnoses are available.

In summary, the diagram illustrates a cyclical diagnostic request mechanism (ID1 -> ID2 -> ID3 -> ID2 -> ID3...) that can be reset to the beginning (`START` state) at any point by requesting `IUMPR_ID1`. Out-of-sequence requests lead to `NR:RSE`, while attempts to read beyond available data, specifically for `IUMPR_ID2` or `IUMPR_ID3` when `last diagnosis reached`, result in `NR:CNC` and system deactivation.
